WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.378 --> 00:00:03.920
FRANK SAVAGE: Good
morning, everyone.

00:00:03.920 --> 00:00:04.600
I'm Frank.

00:00:04.600 --> 00:00:05.890
TIAN LIM: And I'm Tian.

00:00:05.890 --> 00:00:08.140
And we lead Android
games engineering

00:00:08.140 --> 00:00:10.360
and Play product
management at Google.

00:00:10.360 --> 00:00:12.880
First, welcome to GDC.

00:00:12.880 --> 00:00:13.800
[CROWD CHEERING]

00:00:13.800 --> 00:00:17.020
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:18.630 --> 00:00:21.930
We know you have your
choice of 10:00 AM sessions.

00:00:21.930 --> 00:00:24.120
There are only about
1,000 others right now.

00:00:24.120 --> 00:00:27.690
So we appreciate you
being here with us today.

00:00:27.690 --> 00:00:31.020
So like many of
you, we have spent

00:00:31.020 --> 00:00:34.020
our careers and
most of our lives

00:00:34.020 --> 00:00:36.960
playing and building games.

00:00:36.960 --> 00:00:38.880
Pop quiz-- does
anyone here remember

00:00:38.880 --> 00:00:41.130
"Strike Commander" or
"Wing Commander 3" or "Wing

00:00:41.130 --> 00:00:42.380
Commander," in general?

00:00:42.380 --> 00:00:42.530
OK.

00:00:42.530 --> 00:00:43.380
A few.

00:00:43.380 --> 00:00:44.463
That was Frank.

00:00:44.463 --> 00:00:45.630
FRANK SAVAGE: Yeah, that's--

00:00:45.630 --> 00:00:46.130
thank you.

00:00:46.130 --> 00:00:48.640
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:48.640 --> 00:00:50.820
TIAN LIM: To show you
just how hardcore he was,

00:00:50.820 --> 00:00:52.600
this was his license plate.

00:00:52.600 --> 00:00:54.410
You were in high school then?

00:00:54.410 --> 00:00:56.160
FRANK SAVAGE: Well,
it wasn't high school.

00:00:56.160 --> 00:00:57.880
Unfortunately, I was
quite a bit older.

00:00:57.880 --> 00:01:00.450
But, yeah, this was in Chicago.

00:01:00.450 --> 00:01:03.390
And before I had even started
in the games business,

00:01:03.390 --> 00:01:05.129
I may have been a
little bit too large

00:01:05.129 --> 00:01:07.230
of a "Wing Commander" fan, so--

00:01:07.230 --> 00:01:09.504
TIAN LIM: No issue with that.

00:01:09.504 --> 00:01:12.840
For my part, I helped build
the Nintendo GameCube, the Xbox

00:01:12.840 --> 00:01:15.360
360, and the PlayStation 4.

00:01:15.360 --> 00:01:17.610
And to prove my
nerd cred, here's

00:01:17.610 --> 00:01:22.590
an old picture kind of
showing my bad hair choices,

00:01:22.590 --> 00:01:26.340
late at night, as we brought up
the high-performance skidding

00:01:26.340 --> 00:01:28.480
and animation code
for the GameCube

00:01:28.480 --> 00:01:31.110
that was generally used in all
GameCube games and Wii games

00:01:31.110 --> 00:01:33.650
for quite some time.

00:01:33.650 --> 00:01:36.010
FRANK SAVAGE: I spent 17
years working on Xbox.

00:01:36.010 --> 00:01:38.140
I worked on all
three of the Xboxes.

00:01:38.140 --> 00:01:40.390
What I consider to be my
crowning achievement for that

00:01:40.390 --> 00:01:43.360
was, I was the development
manager for XNA Game Studio.

00:01:43.360 --> 00:01:46.330
So if any of you remember
XNA and the XNA framework

00:01:46.330 --> 00:01:49.240
and all that stuff that
Unity is based on today,

00:01:49.240 --> 00:01:51.280
you can blame me for that, too.

00:01:51.280 --> 00:01:54.880
I joined Google because I see
the potential here of Google's

00:01:54.880 --> 00:01:58.060
reach, and really the
expansive capabilities

00:01:58.060 --> 00:02:01.870
that Google has that can really
take your game businesses

00:02:01.870 --> 00:02:04.010
to the next level.

00:02:04.010 --> 00:02:07.260
TIAN LIM: Now, Frank and I also
care deeply about diversity

00:02:07.260 --> 00:02:09.240
in the games business,
and we mean that

00:02:09.240 --> 00:02:12.150
in every sense of the word.

00:02:12.150 --> 00:02:17.190
We live in a world where large
story-driven, triple-A games,

00:02:17.190 --> 00:02:23.130
like "God of War," can live side
by side with a mobile, indie,

00:02:23.130 --> 00:02:26.940
premium title, like "Florence,"
on Game-of-the-Year lists.

00:02:26.940 --> 00:02:28.680
That's absolutely outstanding.

00:02:28.680 --> 00:02:31.590
And so we just care
a lot about fostering

00:02:31.590 --> 00:02:33.810
both ends of that
spectrum, everything

00:02:33.810 --> 00:02:36.570
from large triple-A to small
indie and all the business

00:02:36.570 --> 00:02:41.310
models in-between, from premium,
subscription, ads, and so on.

00:02:43.715 --> 00:02:45.090
FRANK SAVAGE: Your
businesses are

00:02:45.090 --> 00:02:47.070
helping to fuel
incredible growth

00:02:47.070 --> 00:02:49.950
in the global mobile games
market, which are forecasted

00:02:49.950 --> 00:02:52.800
by New Zoo to grow
yearly by double digits

00:02:52.800 --> 00:02:54.480
for the next decade.

00:02:54.480 --> 00:02:59.250
By 2021, mobile games revenue
will be 60% of the global games

00:02:59.250 --> 00:03:01.425
revenue.

00:03:01.425 --> 00:03:03.800
TIAN LIM: And we're seeing
some really interesting trends

00:03:03.800 --> 00:03:08.120
in the industry, like the
explosion of gaming in India,

00:03:08.120 --> 00:03:11.750
which is not traditionally
a huge gaming market.

00:03:11.750 --> 00:03:14.500
And this is, in part, due
to the amazing success

00:03:14.500 --> 00:03:16.390
of "PUBG Mobile."

00:03:16.390 --> 00:03:19.990
This game has become a
cultural phenomenon there.

00:03:19.990 --> 00:03:22.930
The Indian prime minister
has made references to it

00:03:22.930 --> 00:03:26.230
and couples have made
the news by putting out

00:03:26.230 --> 00:03:27.905
PUBG-themed engagement photos.

00:03:30.410 --> 00:03:33.830
But success is not only
for the large developers.

00:03:33.830 --> 00:03:36.920
Every year, we see
inspiring stories,

00:03:36.920 --> 00:03:40.790
like Small Giant Games who
launched "Empires and Puzzles"

00:03:40.790 --> 00:03:43.370
way back in March 2017.

00:03:43.370 --> 00:03:46.340
It became a top-grossing
title on Play last year,

00:03:46.340 --> 00:03:49.366
and they just very recently
got acquired by Zinga.

00:03:49.366 --> 00:03:51.200
It started out as
this tiny team,

00:03:51.200 --> 00:03:52.730
so huge congratulations to them.

00:03:56.050 --> 00:03:58.500
However, as people who have
been around games for quite

00:03:58.500 --> 00:04:01.680
some time, we know that Google
hasn't quite always lived up

00:04:01.680 --> 00:04:03.440
to its potential.

00:04:03.440 --> 00:04:05.940
FRANK SAVAGE: We know we can
improve the experience for game

00:04:05.940 --> 00:04:07.482
developers, and we
want to share some

00:04:07.482 --> 00:04:10.590
of the things we're working
on to make it better for you.

00:04:10.590 --> 00:04:13.750
You'll hear from various Google
teams throughout this week.

00:04:13.750 --> 00:04:16.439
But for now, we'd like to
focus on Android and Play

00:04:16.439 --> 00:04:19.290
and the things that we're doing
there to improve the ecosystem.

00:04:23.660 --> 00:04:26.760
As the engineering lead for
Android games and graphics,

00:04:26.760 --> 00:04:28.850
my team's primary
goal is to help

00:04:28.850 --> 00:04:31.880
you reach more of the 2 billion
Android devices that are there

00:04:31.880 --> 00:04:34.340
by making it easier for
you to build for them.

00:04:34.340 --> 00:04:37.820
We hear your feedback today,
that it's too hard, especially

00:04:37.820 --> 00:04:40.100
when building
high-fidelity games.

00:04:40.100 --> 00:04:42.320
My team's focus
is to build tools

00:04:42.320 --> 00:04:44.240
that will help all
developers bring

00:04:44.240 --> 00:04:46.220
mobile games to the
next level, pushing

00:04:46.220 --> 00:04:49.550
the boundaries on graphics,
multiplayer experiences, and so

00:04:49.550 --> 00:04:51.580
much more.

00:04:51.580 --> 00:04:54.430
Android has traditionally been
one of the toughest platforms

00:04:54.430 --> 00:04:56.380
to develop for-- as
though that's like a badge

00:04:56.380 --> 00:04:58.150
of goodness--

00:04:58.150 --> 00:05:00.460
given the fragmentation of
the ecosystem and limited

00:05:00.460 --> 00:05:02.230
availability of game
development tools

00:05:02.230 --> 00:05:04.000
to deal with this complexity.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:06.670
When you think about
all of the SOC vendors

00:05:06.670 --> 00:05:09.100
that are out there and
all of the different OEMs

00:05:09.100 --> 00:05:11.710
using those SOCs, it's
very, very difficult

00:05:11.710 --> 00:05:14.297
to know what to target to
hit the kinds of things

00:05:14.297 --> 00:05:15.880
that you're going
to be after in terms

00:05:15.880 --> 00:05:18.430
of what your game needs to
do, in terms of performance

00:05:18.430 --> 00:05:20.110
or look and feel.

00:05:20.110 --> 00:05:23.740
At the same time, mobile games
are becoming much more complex.

00:05:23.740 --> 00:05:25.870
With more titles moving
from console and PC

00:05:25.870 --> 00:05:28.030
to mobile, as
developers, you know

00:05:28.030 --> 00:05:30.700
these games need advanced
debugging and development

00:05:30.700 --> 00:05:31.545
tools.

00:05:31.545 --> 00:05:33.670
And those are the kinds of
problems that my team is

00:05:33.670 --> 00:05:36.090
going to be focused on solving.

00:05:36.090 --> 00:05:38.220
To do so, we're
making big investments

00:05:38.220 --> 00:05:40.530
to improve the development
experience on Android.

00:05:40.530 --> 00:05:42.510
We're expanding our scope
and ramping up teams

00:05:42.510 --> 00:05:45.353
to unblock game developers
in problematic areas.

00:05:45.353 --> 00:05:46.770
And also working
with the platform

00:05:46.770 --> 00:05:49.660
teams to build
solutions at scale.

00:05:49.660 --> 00:05:51.430
There are a lot of
hard problems to solve.

00:05:51.430 --> 00:05:54.600
And if you're up for a
challenge, we are hiring.

00:05:54.600 --> 00:05:57.570
TIAN LIM: Hey, you know
I used to optimize games

00:05:57.570 --> 00:05:58.698
for the GameCube, right?

00:05:58.698 --> 00:06:00.240
FRANK SAVAGE: No,
I didn't know that.

00:06:00.240 --> 00:06:02.150
How long has it been
since you goded?

00:06:02.150 --> 00:06:03.765
TIAN LIM: Seven or
eight years, maybe.

00:06:03.765 --> 00:06:05.160
FRANK SAVAGE: Oh,
well, maybe you

00:06:05.160 --> 00:06:06.665
should keep your day job then.

00:06:06.665 --> 00:06:08.804
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:09.780 --> 00:06:11.367
You know, just saying.

00:06:11.367 --> 00:06:13.950
We're also investing in tools
to help give you better insights

00:06:13.950 --> 00:06:14.830
into what's going on.

00:06:14.830 --> 00:06:17.460
We know that the CPU and
GPU profiling stories

00:06:17.460 --> 00:06:20.460
on Android today are not
up to what they need to be.

00:06:20.460 --> 00:06:24.510
We need, again, better
debugging workflows,

00:06:24.510 --> 00:06:26.610
and we're investing in
wider Vulcan availability

00:06:26.610 --> 00:06:29.340
as well, so that you can tap
the graphics potential that's

00:06:29.340 --> 00:06:31.970
in a lot of these
mobile GPUs today.

00:06:31.970 --> 00:06:33.720
We've also heard from
developers that it's

00:06:33.720 --> 00:06:36.390
hard to find information
and resources on mobile game

00:06:36.390 --> 00:06:38.320
development and distribution.

00:06:38.320 --> 00:06:41.130
So to help today, we've
launched a new site

00:06:41.130 --> 00:06:43.920
as a central location
to make great games

00:06:43.920 --> 00:06:45.862
and maximize your reach.

00:06:45.862 --> 00:06:47.820
Keep an eye on this, as
we're going to continue

00:06:47.820 --> 00:06:49.920
to add new resources over time.

00:06:52.440 --> 00:06:55.040
These are just a few
places we're working on

00:06:55.040 --> 00:06:57.872
to make things less complex for
you to build games on Android.

00:06:57.872 --> 00:06:59.330
And we look forward
to sharing more

00:06:59.330 --> 00:07:01.070
with you throughout the year.

00:07:01.070 --> 00:07:03.590
In fact, we'll have
much more to say

00:07:03.590 --> 00:07:06.650
at Google I/O in a brand
new track dedicated entirely

00:07:06.650 --> 00:07:07.550
to games.

00:07:07.550 --> 00:07:09.890
This is the first
time ever that games

00:07:09.890 --> 00:07:11.630
have been featured
at I/O, and this

00:07:11.630 --> 00:07:14.090
speaks to the commitment
across Google,

00:07:14.090 --> 00:07:17.420
because we really want to be the
full lifecycle partner for you

00:07:17.420 --> 00:07:19.370
as you're building these titles.

00:07:19.370 --> 00:07:20.900
If you can't make
the event, please

00:07:20.900 --> 00:07:22.733
make sure to follow
along on the livestream.

00:07:22.733 --> 00:07:26.165
There'll be a lot
of information.

00:07:26.165 --> 00:07:27.540
We know that
developing your game

00:07:27.540 --> 00:07:30.210
doesn't mean the work
stops when you publish.

00:07:30.210 --> 00:07:32.880
This is where you shift
focus to improving the game's

00:07:32.880 --> 00:07:36.030
performance in the marketplace.

00:07:36.030 --> 00:07:37.830
TIAN LIM: And that's
where Play comes in.

00:07:37.830 --> 00:07:40.440
So over the past year, I've
spent a lot of time speaking

00:07:40.440 --> 00:07:43.160
with the game developer
community around the world.

00:07:43.160 --> 00:07:46.590
And a couple things really stand
out that we want to focus on.

00:07:46.590 --> 00:07:48.210
First, discovery.

00:07:48.210 --> 00:07:49.550
It's hard.

00:07:49.550 --> 00:07:52.740
And we want to help your game
succeed on the Play Store.

00:07:52.740 --> 00:07:55.500
Everyday, more
games are appearing,

00:07:55.500 --> 00:07:58.300
but we only have the
same number of pixels.

00:07:58.300 --> 00:08:03.455
And we want to make it easier
for everyone to get discovered.

00:08:03.455 --> 00:08:04.830
Now, we know that
it's especially

00:08:04.830 --> 00:08:08.080
hard for newer and
smaller game developers,

00:08:08.080 --> 00:08:10.350
and we want to do a lot
more to support you.

00:08:10.350 --> 00:08:12.420
So if you visit
our booth starting

00:08:12.420 --> 00:08:15.390
on Wednesday in Center Hall,
you can learn about some

00:08:15.390 --> 00:08:17.670
of the programs that
we run specifically

00:08:17.670 --> 00:08:20.910
for indies that help
amplify your great work,

00:08:20.910 --> 00:08:23.522
such as the Indie
Games Showcase.

00:08:23.522 --> 00:08:25.230
So to learn more,
please go to this site.

00:08:31.260 --> 00:08:33.539
So while we're improving
the storefront,

00:08:33.539 --> 00:08:36.720
we continue to offer
new and effective ways

00:08:36.720 --> 00:08:39.539
to help you distribute
your games to users.

00:08:39.539 --> 00:08:42.150
Last year at GDC, we
announced the launch

00:08:42.150 --> 00:08:45.420
of pre-reg, which allows you to
start marketing and building up

00:08:45.420 --> 00:08:48.780
the pre-launch hype and demand
for your upcoming release.

00:08:48.780 --> 00:08:51.450
This is a tried and true best
practice across the games

00:08:51.450 --> 00:08:55.170
industry, and it helps build
that hype with players.

00:08:55.170 --> 00:08:58.350
You're going to hear some big
news later today about pre-reg

00:08:58.350 --> 00:09:00.490
and some great new features.

00:09:00.490 --> 00:09:06.108
So stay tuned for our session
called "Building the Hype."

00:09:06.108 --> 00:09:08.150
There's a lot more that
we're thinking about when

00:09:08.150 --> 00:09:09.960
it comes to games discovery.

00:09:09.960 --> 00:09:12.440
New games have so much
creativity and so much

00:09:12.440 --> 00:09:14.570
innovation, and then we
tell you to condense it

00:09:14.570 --> 00:09:17.940
into one icon on the
home page of the store.

00:09:17.940 --> 00:09:21.350
So we want to do more to
show the soul of your game

00:09:21.350 --> 00:09:24.500
to users, before they even click
through to the store listing

00:09:24.500 --> 00:09:25.920
page.

00:09:25.920 --> 00:09:27.830
So what you see
here on the left is

00:09:27.830 --> 00:09:30.180
one of our new
auto-playing treatments.

00:09:30.180 --> 00:09:33.200
It should be going out
into experiment this week.

00:09:33.200 --> 00:09:35.060
And in general, you
should be expecting

00:09:35.060 --> 00:09:38.360
to see more and more of
your videos and screenshots

00:09:38.360 --> 00:09:40.805
show up on the home page
over the coming quarters.

00:09:43.700 --> 00:09:49.240
On the right, you will see
our live-ops events page,

00:09:49.240 --> 00:09:52.870
and this can help drive
re-engagement and discovery

00:09:52.870 --> 00:09:56.050
for your live-ops
events and games.

00:09:56.050 --> 00:09:58.520
Major updates can
also be shown here.

00:09:58.520 --> 00:10:00.370
And so in general,
we just want to be

00:10:00.370 --> 00:10:02.950
there to help amplify those
big beats in your business.

00:10:06.810 --> 00:10:09.650
We also launched Google
Play Instant for games

00:10:09.650 --> 00:10:11.680
at GDC last year.

00:10:11.680 --> 00:10:14.800
Players can hit the "Try Now"
button on your store listing

00:10:14.800 --> 00:10:18.610
page and go straight to a
demo experience of your game

00:10:18.610 --> 00:10:22.193
within a matter of seconds
with no installation required.

00:10:22.193 --> 00:10:23.610
FRANK SAVAGE: You
know, I remember

00:10:23.610 --> 00:10:25.750
when we had to cut
discs for demos,

00:10:25.750 --> 00:10:28.860
and we'd glue them to
the fronts of magazines.

00:10:28.860 --> 00:10:30.773
Does anyone remember gluing--

00:10:30.773 --> 00:10:32.940
going to get the disc off
the front of the magazine,

00:10:32.940 --> 00:10:34.513
and then rushing
home and having fun?

00:10:34.513 --> 00:10:35.430
Does anyone miss that?

00:10:35.430 --> 00:10:36.630
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:36.630 --> 00:10:37.230
No?

00:10:37.230 --> 00:10:37.530
OK.

00:10:37.530 --> 00:10:39.363
Well, this is the best
part, is that now you

00:10:39.363 --> 00:10:41.310
can download and play
a match of something

00:10:41.310 --> 00:10:43.690
like "Garena's Free Fire"
in about 10 seconds,

00:10:43.690 --> 00:10:47.380
which is a very, very different
world to be living in.

00:10:47.380 --> 00:10:49.540
TIAN LIM: Great
times we live in.

00:10:49.540 --> 00:10:53.200
We also enabled Instant
for premium titles,

00:10:53.200 --> 00:10:57.880
like HyperBeard's "DR. MEEP,"
an incredibly cute take

00:10:57.880 --> 00:10:58.780
on the match-3 genre.

00:11:02.280 --> 00:11:04.840
We also want to
help you make money.

00:11:04.840 --> 00:11:07.080
We want developers to
have more options on how

00:11:07.080 --> 00:11:09.060
they monetize in general.

00:11:09.060 --> 00:11:11.550
In-app purchases, of
course, are super important.

00:11:11.550 --> 00:11:15.780
But we want to support other
methods, like subscriptions,

00:11:15.780 --> 00:11:18.000
premium games, or rewarded ads.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:21.300
And we're constantly trying
out new approaches here.

00:11:21.300 --> 00:11:24.420
We see huge benefits in
helping developers diversify

00:11:24.420 --> 00:11:26.100
their revenue streams.

00:11:26.100 --> 00:11:27.990
And later today,
you'll hear more

00:11:27.990 --> 00:11:31.230
about the success of
developers, like Playgendary

00:11:31.230 --> 00:11:33.210
and Kongregate.

00:11:33.210 --> 00:11:34.390
Stay tuned.

00:11:34.390 --> 00:11:36.570
We're investing in
even more options,

00:11:36.570 --> 00:11:40.840
and we hope to give you even
more choice in the future.

00:11:40.840 --> 00:11:43.160
So if it isn't
already clear, Google

00:11:43.160 --> 00:11:45.590
is super serious
about helping games

00:11:45.590 --> 00:11:47.600
throughout their lifecycle.

00:11:47.600 --> 00:11:51.290
And if you want learn more, come
to our booth in the West Hall

00:11:51.290 --> 00:11:53.930
or visit our new
Google for Games site.

