I want you to take away

00:24:02.250 --> 00:24:05.220
from this talk, it's dynamic.

00:24:05.220 --> 00:24:08.100
I'll talk about Android App
Bundles and Google Play Dynamic

00:24:08.100 --> 00:24:10.080
Delivery.

00:24:10.080 --> 00:24:13.080
I'll talk about
preparing for 64-bit

00:24:13.080 --> 00:24:15.630
and how you can keep
your users on the latest

00:24:15.630 --> 00:24:18.790
version of your game.

00:24:18.790 --> 00:24:20.168
So let's start with the bundle.

00:24:20.168 --> 00:24:22.210
We launched the Android
App Bundles at Google I/O

00:24:22.210 --> 00:24:26.380
last year, and more than 60,000
apps and games have already

00:24:26.380 --> 00:24:29.860
switched to publishing Android
App Bundles in production

00:24:29.860 --> 00:24:31.470
on Google Play.

00:24:31.470 --> 00:24:33.960
You can build them
with Android Studio,

00:24:33.960 --> 00:24:36.540
you can build with
Unity, and recently, also

00:24:36.540 --> 00:24:39.820
with Cocos Creator.

00:24:39.820 --> 00:24:41.860
In apps and games,
using the app bundle

00:24:41.860 --> 00:24:45.550
becomes smaller, because
Play's Dynamic Delivery only

00:24:45.550 --> 00:24:47.780
sends the device what it needs.

00:24:47.780 --> 00:24:50.860
Our data shows
that, as a result,

00:24:50.860 --> 00:24:54.670
games switching to the
bundle see more than 3%

00:24:54.670 --> 00:24:58.230
increase in their
install success rate.

00:24:58.230 --> 00:25:02.580
Large games benefit even
more, with more than 4%

00:25:02.580 --> 00:25:05.610
install uplift.

00:25:05.610 --> 00:25:08.550
Gameloft's "Minion
Rush, Despicable Me"

00:25:08.550 --> 00:25:10.065
switched to the app bundle.

00:25:10.065 --> 00:25:13.680
It reduced the size of
the game by 20%, which

00:25:13.680 --> 00:25:17.140
is obviously great for
users, and as a result,

00:25:17.140 --> 00:25:20.580
saw more than 3% increase in
their install success rate.

00:25:23.270 --> 00:25:24.790
And there are other
benefits, too.

00:25:24.790 --> 00:25:26.980
It's not just more installs.

00:25:26.980 --> 00:25:29.650
We see that games
switching to bundle get

00:25:29.650 --> 00:25:32.440
more updates, which makes
sense since the update

00:25:32.440 --> 00:25:34.930
patches are smaller, too.

00:25:34.930 --> 00:25:38.050
In addition, we've learned
that the size of the game

00:25:38.050 --> 00:25:41.380
is a major factor in
the uninstall decision.

00:25:41.380 --> 00:25:42.880
We're looking into
this area, and we

00:25:42.880 --> 00:25:45.140
plan to share more
numbers later this year.

00:25:45.140 --> 00:25:48.770
But generally speaking,
the larger your game is,

00:25:48.770 --> 00:25:51.130
the more likely it
will be uninstalled

00:25:51.130 --> 00:25:55.320
by users with limited storage.

00:25:55.320 --> 00:25:56.820
A few months ago,
we shared with you

00:25:56.820 --> 00:25:59.460
that by August we
want you to provide

00:25:59.460 --> 00:26:02.610
64-bit versions of your games.

00:26:02.610 --> 00:26:05.520
This provides tremendous
performance improvements

00:26:05.520 --> 00:26:11.090
and sets you to a world
with 64-bit-only hardware.

00:26:11.090 --> 00:26:13.030
Some concern we've
heard over the years

00:26:13.030 --> 00:26:17.380
is that adding 64-bit support
makes your game bigger,

00:26:17.380 --> 00:26:20.020
because you need to
ship both the 64-bit

00:26:20.020 --> 00:26:22.630
and the 32-bit
libraries to the device.

00:26:22.630 --> 00:26:25.540
With the Android App Bundle,
this is no longer the case.

00:26:25.540 --> 00:26:27.910
Google Play's Dynamic
Delivery will only

00:26:27.910 --> 00:26:30.580
ship the required
libraries based

00:26:30.580 --> 00:26:32.230
on the device architecture.

00:26:32.230 --> 00:26:34.060
And the great thing
here, you don't

00:26:34.060 --> 00:26:36.580
need to do multi-APK
to achieve that.

00:26:36.580 --> 00:26:41.470
You can do this with a
single publishing artifact.

00:26:41.470 --> 00:26:43.990
To learn more about
preparing to 64-bit,

00:26:43.990 --> 00:26:46.600
please join this session
we're co-hosting on Wednesday

00:26:46.600 --> 00:26:47.650
with Arm.

00:26:47.650 --> 00:26:49.240
All the details are right here.

00:26:49.240 --> 00:26:52.851
And please also read our blog
post for more information.

00:26:55.620 --> 00:26:57.690
You all build great
games, and you keeping

00:26:57.690 --> 00:26:59.260
improving them with time.

00:26:59.260 --> 00:27:01.590
And for your users
to take advantage

00:27:01.590 --> 00:27:03.720
of your latest and
greatest features,

00:27:03.720 --> 00:27:06.830
they need to be on the
latest version of your game.

00:27:06.830 --> 00:27:09.560
And you're probably familiar
with Play's auto updates,

00:27:09.560 --> 00:27:12.230
which reach tons of users.

00:27:12.230 --> 00:27:14.970
But given Play's
enormous scale, there

00:27:14.970 --> 00:27:17.850
are always users who
will not be on the latest

00:27:17.850 --> 00:27:21.180
version of your game.

00:27:21.180 --> 00:27:24.420
So recently, we extended
our dynamic framework

00:27:24.420 --> 00:27:29.400
and introduced an early access
program for in-app updates.

00:27:29.400 --> 00:27:32.310
With this API, you
can update your users

00:27:32.310 --> 00:27:34.200
to the latest
version of your game

00:27:34.200 --> 00:27:37.080
without actually sending
them to the Play Store.

00:27:37.080 --> 00:27:39.270
You can see here an
example of how the Chrome

00:27:39.270 --> 00:27:41.940
app is using this API.

00:27:41.940 --> 00:27:46.480
And I want to show you
two flows that we support.

00:27:46.480 --> 00:27:50.370
The first flow is the
immediate update flow.

00:27:50.370 --> 00:27:53.310
This is for cases
when the user must

00:27:53.310 --> 00:27:57.820
be on the latest version of
their game to start playing.

00:27:57.820 --> 00:27:59.920
Today, some multiplayer
games already

00:27:59.920 --> 00:28:02.620
do this kind of blocking
flow, where they send users

00:28:02.620 --> 00:28:04.570
to the Play Store
to get the update

00:28:04.570 --> 00:28:07.210
and ask them to come
back afterwards.

00:28:07.210 --> 00:28:08.860
The great thing
about this new API

00:28:08.860 --> 00:28:12.340
is that it allows you
to do this in line.

00:28:12.340 --> 00:28:14.170
You can keep the
user in your game

00:28:14.170 --> 00:28:16.120
while they download
and install the update.

00:28:18.660 --> 00:28:21.780
The second flow is the
flexible update flow.

00:28:21.780 --> 00:28:25.440
This is for cases where you want
to upsell the latest features

00:28:25.440 --> 00:28:27.630
of your game to your users.

00:28:27.630 --> 00:28:31.890
You can have the user download
the update in the background

00:28:31.890 --> 00:28:35.070
while they keep
playing your game.

00:28:35.070 --> 00:28:37.230
We are ready to expand
the early access

00:28:37.230 --> 00:28:38.970
program to more developers.

00:28:38.970 --> 00:28:42.750
So if you're interested, please
register with this URL right

00:28:42.750 --> 00:28:44.010
here.

00:28:44.010 --> 00:28:47.100
And we are also planning to
launch this to all developers

00:28:47.100 --> 00:28:48.120
publicly, soon.

00:28:51.640 --> 00:28:54.510
Now I want to tell you a little
bit about our future plans

00:28:54.510 --> 00:28:57.220
in the distribution space.

00:28:57.220 --> 00:29:00.490
Mobile devices keep
getting better every year--

00:29:00.490 --> 00:29:03.790
more computation power,
more memory and storage,

00:29:03.790 --> 00:29:05.270
better graphics.

00:29:05.270 --> 00:29:07.840
And as you know better
than anyone else,

00:29:07.840 --> 00:29:10.240
this creates huge
opportunities to deliver

00:29:10.240 --> 00:29:13.670
exciting mobile
gaming experiences.

00:29:13.670 --> 00:29:15.830
We realize that to do
that some games will

00:29:15.830 --> 00:29:18.860
need to be large, because they
have high fidelity graphics

00:29:18.860 --> 00:29:21.210
or have a lot of content.

00:29:21.210 --> 00:29:23.540
We also recognize that
some of the tools that Play

00:29:23.540 --> 00:29:27.560
has provided for large games
over the years, like OBBs,

00:29:27.560 --> 00:29:29.977
were not always the
most optimal ones.

00:29:29.977 --> 00:29:31.435
So the good news
is we're investing

00:29:31.435 --> 00:29:35.860
in this space in 2019.

00:29:35.860 --> 00:29:37.630
Before I tell you
about our future plans,

00:29:37.630 --> 00:29:40.270
I want to make sure you're all
aware of how things actually

00:29:40.270 --> 00:29:44.380
work now, because we made some
changes in this space lately.

00:29:44.380 --> 00:29:46.420
And this is about
how Play validates

00:29:46.420 --> 00:29:49.570
the size of your game
in the Play Console.

00:29:49.570 --> 00:29:54.730
Historically, we've only looked
at the upload size of your APK.

00:29:54.730 --> 00:29:57.340
This doesn't make much sense
in a world of app bundles

00:29:57.340 --> 00:29:59.380
and Play Dynamic
Delivery anymore.

00:29:59.380 --> 00:30:02.600
So recently, we changed the size
validations across the board

00:30:02.600 --> 00:30:04.510
in the Play Console,
and we're now

00:30:04.510 --> 00:30:07.360
only looking at the
compressed download

00:30:07.360 --> 00:30:09.580
size of your APK or app bundle.

00:30:12.520 --> 00:30:13.960
I started this
talk by telling you

00:30:13.960 --> 00:30:16.990
about the immediate benefits
of switching to the app bundle,

00:30:16.990 --> 00:30:20.170
like more installs
and more updates.

00:30:20.170 --> 00:30:22.960
I want to make sure you're
aware that bundles are also

00:30:22.960 --> 00:30:26.740
the future format for
games on Google Play.

00:30:26.740 --> 00:30:28.750
Later this year, we
plan to provide you

00:30:28.750 --> 00:30:32.210
new tools to help you
move away from OBBs.

00:30:32.210 --> 00:30:34.390
This will be based on bundles.

00:30:34.390 --> 00:30:38.290
We're going to provide you new
tools to deliver and optimize

00:30:38.290 --> 00:30:40.270
the delivery of game assets.

00:30:40.270 --> 00:30:43.340
This will be also
based on app bundles.

00:30:43.340 --> 00:30:45.460
So switching to
the bundle not only

00:30:45.460 --> 00:30:48.190
provides immediate
benefits, it sets you up

00:30:48.190 --> 00:30:53.500
to benefit from our future
investment in this area.

00:30:53.500 --> 00:30:56.530
But while it's really exciting
to talk about the future,

00:30:56.530 --> 00:30:58.190
we all live in the present.

00:30:58.190 --> 00:30:59.830
So I want to mention
a couple of things

00:30:59.830 --> 00:31:02.320
that are happening right now.

00:31:02.320 --> 00:31:05.770
You're probably all familiar
with the large download warning

00:31:05.770 --> 00:31:08.050
we show to users
in the Play Store.

00:31:08.050 --> 00:31:10.600
And over the years, we've
heard some developer feedback

00:31:10.600 --> 00:31:13.690
about how this large
warning negatively

00:31:13.690 --> 00:31:17.380
impacts the conversion rate
for large games on Play.

00:31:17.380 --> 00:31:19.790
So we're making a
couple of changes here.

00:31:19.790 --> 00:31:23.800
First of all, we are going to
be more transparent with users

00:31:23.800 --> 00:31:26.720
and tell them the
exact download size.

00:31:26.720 --> 00:31:30.320
As a result, we will no
longer trigger this warning

00:31:30.320 --> 00:31:33.150
when the user is on
a Wi-Fi connection.

00:31:33.150 --> 00:31:35.520
And in addition, we
will make the option

00:31:35.520 --> 00:31:37.395
to proceed with the
download more explicit.

00:31:40.290 --> 00:31:41.640
And one more thing--

00:31:41.640 --> 00:31:44.820
we will no longer trigger
this warning at 100 megabytes.

00:31:44.820 --> 00:31:47.810
Starting today, we are
triggering this warning

00:31:47.810 --> 00:31:49.950
at 150 megabytes.

00:31:49.950 --> 00:31:53.310
[APPLAUSE]

00:31:55.720 --> 00:31:58.380
The size limit of the
Android app bundle

00:31:58.380 --> 00:32:00.300
will be increased
to 150 megabytes

00:32:00.300 --> 00:32:03.440
to make sure you could
take advantage of this.

00:32:03.440 --> 00:32:06.390
We are currently keeping the
size limit for APKs on 100,

00:32:06.390 --> 00:32:09.600
but you can still use APK and
OBB until we completely revise

00:32:09.600 --> 00:32:13.180
this space later this year.

00:32:13.180 --> 00:32:16.950
So today I talked to you
about our dynamic framework.

00:32:16.950 --> 00:32:18.960
I spoke about the
immediate benefits

00:32:18.960 --> 00:32:21.870
of switching to app
bundles, like more installs

00:32:21.870 --> 00:32:23.580
and more updates.

00:32:23.580 --> 00:32:26.620
I showed you how it better
sets you for a 64-bit

00:32:26.620 --> 00:32:29.070
and about our
latest API, allowing

00:32:29.070 --> 00:32:32.910
you to keep your users on the
latest version of your game.

00:32:32.910 --> 00:32:35.130
Finally, I told you
about some of our plans

00:32:35.130 --> 00:32:38.100
to better support large games
on Google Play and about

00:32:38.100 --> 00:32:40.080
some changes that
are happening today,

00:32:40.080 --> 00:32:43.252
like the new 150-megabyte
limit threshold.

00:32:43.252 --> 00:32:44.460
I hope you enjoyed this talk.

00:32:44.460 --> 00:32:45.613
Thank you for joining.

00:32:45.613 --> 00:32:48.030
Now, I'd like to call Fergus
to talk about Android vitals.

00:32:48.030 --> 00:32:51.280
[APPLAUSE]

00:32:51.780 --> 00:32:52.988
FERGUS HURLEY: Hey, everyone.

00:32:52.988 --> 00:32:55.020
I'm Fergus Hurley,
Product Manager at Google.

00:32:55.020 --> 00:32:57.090
Android vitals is
a program by Google

00:32:57.090 --> 00:32:59.820
to help improve the
quality of games and apps

00:32:59.820 --> 00:33:01.158
on the Android ecosystem.

00:33:01.158 --> 00:33:03.450
And we've been running this
program for about two years

00:33:03.450 --> 00:33:03.590
now.

00:33:03.590 --> 00:33:05.130
And I'm going to give you
an overview of the program.

00:33:05.130 --> 00:33:07.968
And then we're going to have
Felipe from Tapps Games come

00:33:07.968 --> 00:33:10.260
to stage and talk you through
how they're using Android

00:33:10.260 --> 00:33:12.180
vitals and a bunch
of other tools

00:33:12.180 --> 00:33:14.550
to help improve the
performance of the many games

00:33:14.550 --> 00:33:17.300
