01:00:07.780 --> 01:00:09.780
And as such, they're using
lifetime value metric

01:00:09.780 --> 01:00:11.055
for many purposes.

01:00:11.055 --> 01:00:12.930
So the first one is like
marketing viability,

01:00:12.930 --> 01:00:14.280
which we spoke already.

01:00:14.280 --> 01:00:16.790
So how far we can
push those CPIs

01:00:16.790 --> 01:00:19.260
and how much we can invest
in acquiring a user.

01:00:19.260 --> 01:00:21.780
But also, we see a
lot of developers

01:00:21.780 --> 01:00:24.240
thinking about live-ops and
running some of the offers,

01:00:24.240 --> 01:00:27.030
running some of the
promotions within the game.

01:00:27.030 --> 01:00:28.770
As well, if we
think even bolder,

01:00:28.770 --> 01:00:31.110
we can think about
product prioritization.

01:00:31.110 --> 01:00:32.780
We can think about
new games, if we

01:00:32.780 --> 01:00:36.720
are looking to improve our LTV
across the portfolio of games

01:00:36.720 --> 01:00:37.840
that we have.

01:00:37.840 --> 01:00:40.620
And last but not least, if
we subtract some of the cost

01:00:40.620 --> 01:00:43.500
and we think about it
in net terms of LTV,

01:00:43.500 --> 01:00:46.820
we can think about
the profit margins.

01:00:46.820 --> 01:00:49.280
So as an example,
GameHouse is a developer

01:00:49.280 --> 01:00:51.190
based in the
Netherlands and Spain,

01:00:51.190 --> 01:00:53.870
and they're using lifetime
value to do many of the things

01:00:53.870 --> 01:00:54.620
that we mentioned.

01:00:54.620 --> 01:00:56.230
So they're doing
user acquisition.

01:00:56.230 --> 01:00:59.180
They are doing remarketing,
re-engagement, retargeting,

01:00:59.180 --> 01:01:01.550
and they're even
thinking about LiveOps

01:01:01.550 --> 01:01:05.480
for the new game,
"Doctor's Oath."

01:01:05.480 --> 01:01:07.910
So in an ideal world,
our lifetime value metric

01:01:07.910 --> 01:01:09.200
would look like in this way.

01:01:09.200 --> 01:01:11.450
So it would be predictive,
where we're looking forward

01:01:11.450 --> 01:01:15.382
rather than just
like historical data.

01:01:15.382 --> 01:01:17.840
It would be a metric that is
extremely accurate, because we

01:01:17.840 --> 01:01:21.170
need to take decisions with a
certain degree of confidence.

01:01:21.170 --> 01:01:23.870
It would be also looking at an
individual level rather than

01:01:23.870 --> 01:01:24.610
cohorts.

01:01:24.610 --> 01:01:25.598
And it would be fast.

01:01:25.598 --> 01:01:27.140
From the very first
day, we will know

01:01:27.140 --> 01:01:28.790
what is the value
that this player is

01:01:28.790 --> 01:01:31.400
going to bring in its lifetime.

01:01:31.400 --> 01:01:32.900
As well, the model
that we're using,

01:01:32.900 --> 01:01:34.400
it would be fast
and simple, meaning

01:01:34.400 --> 01:01:36.770
that we don't have
to spend months

01:01:36.770 --> 01:01:38.690
in order to train this model.

01:01:38.690 --> 01:01:40.190
But the first thing
that you learn

01:01:40.190 --> 01:01:42.440
when you start researching
about lifetime value

01:01:42.440 --> 01:01:45.230
is that there is no standard
way of calculating it,

01:01:45.230 --> 01:01:47.630
which means that this
comes with some trade-offs

01:01:47.630 --> 01:01:49.100
and some challenges.

01:01:49.100 --> 01:01:51.740
We asked Plarium, an
Israeli developer,

01:01:51.740 --> 01:01:53.720
the creator of
"Vikings, War of Clans,"

01:01:53.720 --> 01:01:56.665
and they told us they
faced three key challenges.

01:01:56.665 --> 01:01:58.790
The first one is how to
estimate the lifetime value

01:01:58.790 --> 01:02:00.380
for a certain type of players.

01:02:00.380 --> 01:02:01.880
They call it outliers,
and these are

01:02:01.880 --> 01:02:04.460
players that they might
be highly engaged,

01:02:04.460 --> 01:02:06.680
but still, they are non-payers.

01:02:06.680 --> 01:02:09.770
As well, they have multiple
games in their portfolio.

01:02:09.770 --> 01:02:11.420
And it's very difficult
for them to use

01:02:11.420 --> 01:02:14.420
one unique model that
really is adjusting

01:02:14.420 --> 01:02:17.540
to every type of game.

01:02:17.540 --> 01:02:19.580
And last but not
least, the long window

01:02:19.580 --> 01:02:21.700
that is needed to validate
these models, in fact,

01:02:21.700 --> 01:02:23.830
is higher than expected.

01:02:23.830 --> 01:02:26.380
But whenever we are
talking about developers,

01:02:26.380 --> 01:02:28.770
they see that these
models, all of them, they

01:02:28.770 --> 01:02:31.840
have several common
things, common areas.

01:02:31.840 --> 01:02:33.810
In this case, we
could have split

01:02:33.810 --> 01:02:35.310
lifetime value in three areas.

01:02:35.310 --> 01:02:39.270
And the first one we would
talk about, what is lifetime?

01:02:39.270 --> 01:02:42.360
That is generally represented
in daily retention,

01:02:42.360 --> 01:02:43.830
and this is a classic way.

01:02:43.830 --> 01:02:45.300
But here, many
developers, they are

01:02:45.300 --> 01:02:48.570
starting to think about whether
the classic retention is

01:02:48.570 --> 01:02:50.862
like the one that makes more
sense for their own game,

01:02:50.862 --> 01:02:52.320
and they can think
about other ways

01:02:52.320 --> 01:02:55.080
of calculating retention,
such as, for example, range

01:02:55.080 --> 01:02:56.640
or rolling retention.

01:02:56.640 --> 01:02:58.860
Also, think about retention,
it means, right now,

01:02:58.860 --> 01:02:59.820
opening the app.

01:02:59.820 --> 01:03:02.220
But it is not the same as if
we're opening the game just

01:03:02.220 --> 01:03:05.820
to collect the daily reward
or to play another battle.

01:03:05.820 --> 01:03:07.360
The second area
would be the value.

01:03:07.360 --> 01:03:08.735
And this is
generally represented

01:03:08.735 --> 01:03:13.457
by purchases or by averages,
such as ARPDAU or ARPPU.

01:03:13.457 --> 01:03:15.540
And in this case, if you
are considering averages,

01:03:15.540 --> 01:03:18.840
it's very important to take into
account, as well, how long are

01:03:18.840 --> 01:03:20.010
you going backwards?

01:03:20.010 --> 01:03:23.400
Let's imagine that, for example,
you ran an offer last week.

01:03:23.400 --> 01:03:25.900
And then last but not
least is the period.

01:03:25.900 --> 01:03:28.410
So how far are we going
into the future in order

01:03:28.410 --> 01:03:30.080
to estimate our lifetime value?

01:03:30.080 --> 01:03:32.830
And generally, from my
conversations with developers,

01:03:32.830 --> 01:03:35.070
it all comes down
to two things--

01:03:35.070 --> 01:03:38.910
the nature of the game, and as
well, how well-funded are we

01:03:38.910 --> 01:03:42.840
in terms of acquiring users
for like a period of 180 days

01:03:42.840 --> 01:03:45.210
or 365 days.

01:03:45.210 --> 01:03:47.380
Here we have an example
that I just mentioned.

01:03:47.380 --> 01:03:51.220
For example, in this case, we
are taking the ARPPU of a user

01:03:51.220 --> 01:03:54.940
and we are projecting
for 180 days.

01:03:54.940 --> 01:03:56.670
So other things that
developers take into

01:03:56.670 --> 01:03:59.440
account when they refer
to lifetime value.

01:03:59.440 --> 01:04:02.040
So we have, first
of all, how do we

01:04:02.040 --> 01:04:03.990
integrate all the
different business models

01:04:03.990 --> 01:04:06.210
that we are monetizing nowadays?

01:04:06.210 --> 01:04:09.330
So how do we include
in-app purchases together

01:04:09.330 --> 01:04:11.700
with subscriptions
and together with ads?

01:04:11.700 --> 01:04:13.500
As well, if you are
a developer that

01:04:13.500 --> 01:04:15.960
has multiple games
in your portfolio

01:04:15.960 --> 01:04:18.060
and you are running some
sort of in-house ads

01:04:18.060 --> 01:04:20.100
and cross-promotions,
it is the best practice,

01:04:20.100 --> 01:04:22.558
that some developers, they're
thinking about their lifetime

01:04:22.558 --> 01:04:24.780
value across their
whole portfolio.

01:04:24.780 --> 01:04:26.870
Last but not least, we're
talking about, as well,

01:04:26.870 --> 01:04:28.890
virality and K-factor effect.

01:04:28.890 --> 01:04:31.050
So this might not affect
the lifetime value,

01:04:31.050 --> 01:04:33.800
but indeed affects the
return on ads spent.

01:04:33.800 --> 01:04:36.210
And some other areas
that developers can see,

01:04:36.210 --> 01:04:38.940
there is, as I said
before, net LTV.

01:04:38.940 --> 01:04:41.357
Also, the frequency when
we do these calculations,

01:04:41.357 --> 01:04:43.440
and what are the segments
that we are using, if we

01:04:43.440 --> 01:04:46.360
are applying averages.

01:04:46.360 --> 01:04:48.510
So I tried to cluster,
which is very difficult.

01:04:48.510 --> 01:04:51.880
I tried to cluster all these
models into three areas.

01:04:51.880 --> 01:04:53.820
So the first one, if
we have small data,

01:04:53.820 --> 01:04:56.250
we have to make
decisions, we can

01:04:56.250 --> 01:04:58.420
see that these simple
predictive models,

01:04:58.420 --> 01:05:00.210
which are looking at averages--

01:05:00.210 --> 01:05:01.890
we are trying to
estimate based on this,

01:05:01.890 --> 01:05:04.200
for example, a
bottoms-up approach

01:05:04.200 --> 01:05:05.160
or a top-down approach.

01:05:05.160 --> 01:05:08.370
We are trying to estimate
the lifetime value of a user.

01:05:08.370 --> 01:05:10.920
You have a number of tools
available today in the Play

01:05:10.920 --> 01:05:13.590
Console, and, as well,
in some analytical tools,

01:05:13.590 --> 01:05:16.680
such as Firebase, where you
can extract this information

01:05:16.680 --> 01:05:19.380
and start working
around these models.

01:05:19.380 --> 01:05:23.130
If you have more data and
you have more mature games,

01:05:23.130 --> 01:05:25.770
actually, also you have
more resources to dedicate,

01:05:25.770 --> 01:05:28.930
you can think about these
predictive statistical models,

01:05:28.930 --> 01:05:31.320
which generally they're
coming from the offline world,

01:05:31.320 --> 01:05:32.820
and they are backed by academia.

01:05:32.820 --> 01:05:34.680
And you have a couple
of examples here--

01:05:34.680 --> 01:05:36.590
Pareto-NBD, BG-NBD.

01:05:36.590 --> 01:05:39.180
The good news is that
they are open-source,

01:05:39.180 --> 01:05:40.740
and you can download
the libraries.

01:05:40.740 --> 01:05:43.800
In this case, I put
Lifetimes Python library,

01:05:43.800 --> 01:05:46.660
which is open for everyone, and
you can start playing around.

01:05:46.660 --> 01:05:49.740
The good news is it will have
individual predictive lifetime

01:05:49.740 --> 01:05:50.660
values already.

01:05:50.660 --> 01:05:53.252
And it would be very helpful
if you want to run live-ops.

01:05:53.252 --> 01:05:55.710
And then last but not least,
we have the predictive machine

01:05:55.710 --> 01:05:56.640
learning models--

01:05:56.640 --> 01:05:59.848
way more sophisticated, a
bit more complex, as well.

01:05:59.848 --> 01:06:01.390
But they're extremely
helpful, if you

01:06:01.390 --> 01:06:03.557
are trying to understand
what are the behaviors that

01:06:03.557 --> 01:06:06.745
are driving certain actions,
such as making purchases.

01:06:06.745 --> 01:06:09.120
If you want to start-- like
we have Firebase predictions.

01:06:09.120 --> 01:06:11.090
There is going to be a
session later on today.

01:06:11.090 --> 01:06:15.930
And you can think about
using these as a first step

01:06:15.930 --> 01:06:17.377
into these type of models.

01:06:17.377 --> 01:06:18.960
Obviously, if you
have more resources,

01:06:18.960 --> 01:06:21.660
you can use Tensor
Flow or AutoML

01:06:21.660 --> 01:06:24.810
to build your own algorithms
based on random forest

01:06:24.810 --> 01:06:27.600
or neuronal networks.

01:06:27.600 --> 01:06:30.260
So GameHouse, the same developer
that I was mentioning before,

01:06:30.260 --> 01:06:33.350
they use historical data
combined with machine learning,

01:06:33.350 --> 01:06:37.580
and they're able to estimate
a lifetime value within a week

01:06:37.580 --> 01:06:40.148
with 90% accuracy.

01:06:40.148 --> 01:06:41.190
So which one is the best?

01:06:41.190 --> 01:06:43.310
This is the most
trickiest question.

01:06:43.310 --> 01:06:46.583
I would say, in this case, also
the answer would be it depends.

01:06:46.583 --> 01:06:48.000
It depends on your
resources, what

01:06:48.000 --> 01:06:50.470
you want to do with this
metric, and how much effort

01:06:50.470 --> 01:06:51.470
you want to put into it.

01:06:51.470 --> 01:06:54.410
If you, for example, don't
have too much data or too much

01:06:54.410 --> 01:06:56.690
resources, some of the
simple predictive models

01:06:56.690 --> 01:06:57.830
would be interesting.

01:06:57.830 --> 01:07:01.490
If you, for example, have a very
clear focus on user acquisition

01:07:01.490 --> 01:07:03.600
and you have the data
and the resources,

01:07:03.600 --> 01:07:05.600
some of these machine
learning predictive models

01:07:05.600 --> 01:07:08.270
could be very helpful
in order to understand

01:07:08.270 --> 01:07:11.390
the likelihood of a new
player becoming a payer.

01:07:11.390 --> 01:07:13.310
And then, if you
have a mature game

01:07:13.310 --> 01:07:15.590
with lots of data and
highly-engaged users,

01:07:15.590 --> 01:07:18.120
you can think about
predictive statistical models,

01:07:18.120 --> 01:07:22.495
which they run very well
to calculate live-ops.

01:07:22.495 --> 01:07:24.870
I want to spend the last two
minutes talking about a case

01:07:24.870 --> 01:07:25.430
study.

01:07:25.430 --> 01:07:29.367
Space Ape is a developer
from the UK founded in 2012.

01:07:29.367 --> 01:07:30.950
And he's the creator
of popular games,

01:07:30.950 --> 01:07:33.445
such as "Samurai
Siege" and "Fastlane."

01:07:33.445 --> 01:07:34.820
In this case, the
Space Ape, they

01:07:34.820 --> 01:07:37.310
calculated the lifetime value
based on historical data

01:07:37.310 --> 01:07:39.200
and using statistical models.

01:07:39.200 --> 01:07:42.500
They have data for
about one to six months.

01:07:42.500 --> 01:07:45.170
And after the day two,
they are able to estimate

01:07:45.170 --> 01:07:48.650
what is going to be the lifetime
value with an 80% to 90%

01:07:48.650 --> 01:07:49.760
accuracy.

01:07:49.760 --> 01:07:51.920
The way they do it is
they create segments

01:07:51.920 --> 01:07:54.350
based on tenure,
based on geography,

01:07:54.350 --> 01:07:57.080
and they multiply the
revenues generated

01:07:57.080 --> 01:07:59.540
of that particular
player by a ratio

01:07:59.540 --> 01:08:02.430
that they estimate
based on their models.

01:08:02.430 --> 01:08:05.540
So the LTV is mainly used for
user-acquisition purposes,

01:08:05.540 --> 01:08:10.070
but also Space Ape
uses it for live-ops.

01:08:10.070 --> 01:08:13.580
The LTV metric is
refreshed on a daily basis.

01:08:13.580 --> 01:08:17.270
And they have two interesting
additional LTV metrics.

01:08:17.270 --> 01:08:21.020
One is called LTV+, which
essentially is adding a small

01:08:21.020 --> 01:08:24.770
percentage to these metrics
and is used only for user

01:08:24.770 --> 01:08:25.800
acquisition purposes.

01:08:25.800 --> 01:08:30.020
And this is to take into account
the virality or the K-factor.

01:08:30.020 --> 01:08:32.330
Then, the second
one is the ad LTV.

01:08:32.330 --> 01:08:35.149
And what they are doing
is, thanks to partnerships

01:08:35.149 --> 01:08:38.090
with networks, they are
trying to understand

01:08:38.090 --> 01:08:40.670
what goes beyond the
ad view and even what

01:08:40.670 --> 01:08:43.490
would be the conversion
of a particular player

01:08:43.490 --> 01:08:46.770
when they see a rewarded
ad, for example.

01:08:46.770 --> 01:08:50.120
So in essence, for Space
Ape, lifetime value

01:08:50.120 --> 01:08:53.180
is a critical metric,
and they aim to actually

01:08:53.180 --> 01:08:55.430
have a return in that
span of at least 100%

01:08:55.430 --> 01:08:56.887
in the first two months.

01:08:56.887 --> 01:08:59.220
So with this, I would like
to conclude with four things.

01:08:59.220 --> 01:09:01.040
So the first one
is, remember, we

01:09:01.040 --> 01:09:03.380
are using lifetime value for
user acquisition purposes,

01:09:03.380 --> 01:09:07.819
but you can use it, as well, for
other topics or other purposes,

01:09:07.819 --> 01:09:11.840
such as live-ops, or
in this case, net LTV.

01:09:11.840 --> 01:09:14.810
As well, when possible, try
to use a predictive model,

01:09:14.810 --> 01:09:15.950
an individual.

01:09:15.950 --> 01:09:17.848
And as well, consider
other things,

01:09:17.848 --> 01:09:19.640
such as how are we
going to use this model?

01:09:19.640 --> 01:09:22.290
How are we going
to use this metric?

01:09:22.290 --> 01:09:25.430
And if we have, for example,
multiple apps in our portfolio,

01:09:25.430 --> 01:09:28.649
how are we going to incorporate
other business models?

01:09:28.649 --> 01:09:31.200
Now, last but not least,
predicting the future obviously

01:09:31.200 --> 01:09:33.859
is not 100% accurate
science, so take these more

01:09:33.859 --> 01:09:37.479
as a tool and as a metric
rather than just a goal.

